30
00:01:43.140 --> 00:01:46.660
So I'm going to start by talking about why the NCI is

31
00:01:46.700 --> 00:01:50.500
exploring the use of federated learning and how we got started with the

32
00:01:50.540 --> 00:01:51.420
FLAME Consortium.

33
00:01:52.620 --> 00:01:56.060
And FLAME stands for Federated Learning-based AI in

34
00:01:56.160 --> 00:01:58.840
Multimodal Exploration.

35
00:02:01.130 --> 00:02:04.980
So our interest in federated learning is really to overcome

36
00:02:05.060 --> 00:02:08.660
challenges to better harness the use of AI to improve cancer

37
00:02:08.741 --> 00:02:12.680
research and patient care. As I'm sure you all know,

38
00:02:12.980 --> 00:02:16.620
strong AI models depend on access to large,

39
00:02:16.760 --> 00:02:19.160
diverse, and representative data sets.

40
00:02:19.900 --> 00:02:21.800
And that's where we run into challenges.

41
00:02:22.800 --> 00:02:26.360
Cancer data are spread across hospitals and research centers,

42
00:02:27.000 --> 00:02:30.500
and legal and regulatory and competitive barriers

43
00:02:31.020 --> 00:02:33.140
often make it difficult to share these data.

44
00:02:34.200 --> 00:02:38.060
But we need broader access to it to realize the promise of

45
00:02:38.100 --> 00:02:38.480
AI.

46
00:02:39.520 --> 00:02:43.340
For example, rare cancers and specific subtypes may

47
00:02:43.420 --> 00:02:46.080
only exist in small numbers at any one site.

48
00:02:47.100 --> 00:02:48.820
And in many data sets

49
00:02:50.800 --> 00:02:51.520
underrepresent

50
00:02:52.780 --> 00:02:56.240
important groups, for example, rural patients or minority

51
00:02:56.340 --> 00:02:57.220
populations.

52
00:02:58.620 --> 00:03:02.580
Another issue is that models trained at a single institution often

53
00:03:02.620 --> 00:03:06.520
don't perform well elsewhere because patient populations and

54
00:03:06.580 --> 00:03:10.280
clinical practices can differ significantly across institutions.

55
00:03:12.440 --> 00:03:15.660
So federated learning offers a potential way forward.

56
00:03:16.540 --> 00:03:20.460
Instead of moving data to a central location, it allows

57
00:03:20.520 --> 00:03:24.100
us to bring the model to the data for training, enabling

58
00:03:24.160 --> 00:03:27.880
collaboration across institutions while keeping sensitive

59
00:03:27.940 --> 00:03:31.900
information secure and local. And in doing so, this

60
00:03:31.980 --> 00:03:35.760
opens the door to learning from broader, more diverse data sets

61
00:03:36.420 --> 00:03:40.100
and creating AI models that are more robust and generalizable.

62
00:03:42.680 --> 00:03:46.370
So let me walk you through how federated learning works at a high level.

63
00:03:47.700 --> 00:03:51.670
Federated learning starts with initializing a global model on a central

64
00:03:51.720 --> 00:03:55.500
server, and this model is the basis from which the

65
00:03:55.560 --> 00:03:57.760
federated learning process begins.

66
00:03:59.420 --> 00:04:02.880
This model is provided to each of the sites in the network.

67
00:04:04.100 --> 00:04:08.080
Now, each institution keeps its data locally and trains that

68
00:04:08.160 --> 00:04:09.700
model on its own data.

69
00:04:10.700 --> 00:04:14.480
The data could include clinical records, imaging, genomic

70
00:04:14.560 --> 00:04:16.399
data, depending on the task.

71
00:04:18.000 --> 00:04:21.840
After a round of training at each site, instead of sharing raw

72
00:04:21.940 --> 00:04:25.510
data, each site sends only the model updates,

73
00:04:25.600 --> 00:04:29.190
essentially what the model has learned, to a central coordinating

74
00:04:29.280 --> 00:04:29.640
server.

75
00:04:30.460 --> 00:04:34.280
And this server aggregates these updates to create an improved global

76
00:04:34.340 --> 00:04:38.220
model, which is then sent back to all the participating

77
00:04:38.260 --> 00:04:42.240
institutions. And this process can be repeated multiple times,

78
00:04:42.710 --> 00:04:46.480
allowing the model to learn from a much broader and more diverse data

79
00:04:46.580 --> 00:04:50.220
set, again, without the data ever having to leave its original

80
00:04:50.280 --> 00:04:50.960
location.

81
00:04:51.820 --> 00:04:55.700
And so the federated learning enables collaboration

82
00:04:55.740 --> 00:04:57.080
across institutions,

83
00:04:58.140 --> 00:05:01.700
ideally improving model robustness and helps protect patient

84
00:05:01.780 --> 00:05:02.280
privacy.

85
00:05:06.860 --> 00:05:10.600
So to explore the feasibility of federated learning across cancer

86
00:05:10.620 --> 00:05:14.120
centers, the NCI initiated the FLAME Consortium in

87
00:05:14.180 --> 00:05:15.030
2003.

88
00:05:16.040 --> 00:05:19.600
The original goals of the FLAME Consortium were really proof of concept.

89
00:05:19.920 --> 00:05:20.940
Specifically,

90
00:05:22.300 --> 00:05:26.280
testing whether sites could exchange a model and federate using

91
00:05:26.320 --> 00:05:29.520
a common technical infrastructure and governance approach.

92
00:05:30.800 --> 00:05:33.680
The founding FLAME sites were the NCI,

93
00:05:34.860 --> 00:05:37.790
CHOP, and OHSU in 2003.

94
00:05:38.740 --> 00:05:39.790
In 2004,

95
00:05:40.720 --> 00:05:44.360
we added University of Hawaii, Moffitt Cancer Center, and Wake

96
00:05:44.460 --> 00:05:48.180
Forest. And finally, in 2005, two more sites

97
00:05:48.280 --> 00:05:52.100
joined, UT Health Houston and Medical University of

98
00:05:52.160 --> 00:05:56.120
South Carolina, bringing us to eight total sites in the FLAME Consortium.

99
00:05:57.280 --> 00:06:00.840
So with that, I'd like to now hand it over to Shannon Silkensohn, who'll tell you

100
00:06:00.920 --> 00:06:03.640
more about the consortium's infrastructure and governance.

101
00:06:13.210 --> 00:06:17.010
Thank you so much, Julie. I'm really delighted to share with you all a little bit

102
00:06:17.070 --> 00:06:20.500
about the operationalizing our network for federated learning.

103
00:06:20.840 --> 00:06:24.770
I'm going to focus on three things: the infrastructure, the capabilities,

104
00:06:24.810 --> 00:06:26.990
and the governance. This is really the meat of the talk.

105
00:06:27.030 --> 00:06:29.060
You guys look up, get off your phone.

106
00:06:29.090 --> 00:06:31.830
You're going to love it when I get to governance. All right.

107
00:06:32.470 --> 00:06:35.250
So what makes this collaboration novel?

108
00:06:35.770 --> 00:06:39.210
So traditionally, everything sort of happened sequentially, right?

109
00:06:39.270 --> 00:06:42.119
You'd stand up some governance, you stand up some infrastructure, you'd get the

110
00:06:42.170 --> 00:06:45.830
data together, you'd pull together a model, and this sort of linear

111
00:06:45.870 --> 00:06:49.790
process took a really long time. So we said, "Hey, what if we

112
00:06:49.810 --> 00:06:53.690
were to turn this on its head and just do everything all at once?" And so

113
00:06:53.750 --> 00:06:57.630
we worked with different teams to stand up the governance, to work through

114
00:06:57.690 --> 00:07:00.619
the infrastructure that is needed, and to gather the data sets.

115
00:07:01.060 --> 00:07:04.730
And by working together sort of collaboratively all at once, we were

116
00:07:04.790 --> 00:07:08.650
really able to condense the time probably down from 12 months to four

117
00:07:08.690 --> 00:07:10.330
months, and it was really super great.

118
00:07:11.450 --> 00:07:11.630
So

119
00:07:12.770 --> 00:07:15.750
one of the things that's really important, and we've heard a lot about here is

120
00:07:15.850 --> 00:07:18.980
about protecting patient privacy and patient data.

121
00:07:19.670 --> 00:07:23.610
And so with federated learning, as Julie mentioned, the data stays

122
00:07:23.650 --> 00:07:26.870
locally behind the institution's firewall. It doesn't leave.

123
00:07:27.930 --> 00:07:31.250
So what does leave are these things called weights.

124
00:07:31.350 --> 00:07:34.510
So if you have a model, there's different weights that are placed on the different

125
00:07:34.550 --> 00:07:38.370
types of data, and they go into a secure place for aggregation, so that,

126
00:07:38.430 --> 00:07:42.370
again, you can learn from patients that are all sites without the

127
00:07:42.390 --> 00:07:43.910
data leaving the home institution.

128
00:07:46.090 --> 00:07:49.960
So this is the good part. One of the things that was great about this

129
00:07:49.970 --> 00:07:53.030
consortium is we set up a two-tier governance structure.

130
00:07:53.490 --> 00:07:57.290
So the first tier was at the top, it was at the consortium level, and it had a

131
00:07:57.330 --> 00:08:01.070
member agreement and bylaws. Member agreement is a super long

132
00:08:01.150 --> 00:08:04.770
document. It has rules, responsibilities, publications, IP,

133
00:08:04.890 --> 00:08:08.770
security. We could keep going, and this is what really gets signed by each

134
00:08:08.830 --> 00:08:12.550
institution. We also put together a lightweight set of bylaws,

135
00:08:12.690 --> 00:08:15.870
operational procedures about how to run an effective consortium.

136
00:08:16.450 --> 00:08:20.090
The great thing is, once your institution signs the member consortium, you are part

137
00:08:20.130 --> 00:08:23.730
of our team. You're a part of our family. It's amazing.

138
00:08:23.790 --> 00:08:27.270
And then we set up this lower level of project governance.

139
00:08:27.310 --> 00:08:29.390
And so this was at the project level.

140
00:08:29.910 --> 00:08:33.670
So when you have federated learning, you have multiple sites, but not all sites

141
00:08:33.711 --> 00:08:35.270
might want to participate in the same model.

142
00:08:35.691 --> 00:08:39.030
So you set up this little transactional agreement between the two sites that want

143
00:08:39.050 --> 00:08:42.770
to work together and collaborate data. It's lightweight. It describes a project.

144
00:08:42.831 --> 00:08:45.910
You can do it really quickly. So speaking of describing the

145
00:08:45.950 --> 00:08:49.710
project, one of the other things that we found to really help us

146
00:08:50.090 --> 00:08:53.890
was we set up these model cards that had the technical specifications that were

147
00:08:53.990 --> 00:08:57.390
needed for the model. How much data you need, what the

148
00:08:57.410 --> 00:09:01.230
objective was like, what type of compute you needed to see if your

149
00:09:01.250 --> 00:09:05.070
organization was really even able to participate and federate with

150
00:09:05.110 --> 00:09:06.890
somebody else who was part of this team.

151
00:09:09.030 --> 00:09:12.950
And as Julia said before, just to remind you, I don't know your level of

152
00:09:13.010 --> 00:09:14.390
federated learning knowledge here.

153
00:09:14.950 --> 00:09:18.870
So you have the different sites A, B, C, and D, and each of them

154
00:09:18.930 --> 00:09:21.930
have their own data sets behind their institutional firewall.

155
00:09:22.450 --> 00:09:26.050
You've got the central model. It gets shared out north, south, east, and west.

156
00:09:26.190 --> 00:09:29.300
You aggregate it together to get the final model with the weight and the

157
00:09:29.350 --> 00:09:30.710
contribution from all the sites.

158
00:09:32.170 --> 00:09:35.430
So what's really cool about this is this infrastructure enables us

159
00:09:35.470 --> 00:09:38.530
to create multimodal models in effect.

160
00:09:38.970 --> 00:09:42.830
So you can take your imaging data, whether it's radiology or pathology, and you

161
00:09:42.890 --> 00:09:46.350
can align it with your lab results and your clinical reports.

162
00:09:46.490 --> 00:09:49.959
And when you bring this together in a model, you get a more comprehensive view of

163
00:09:49.990 --> 00:09:53.270
the patient that, again, you're able to share across your institutions.

164
00:09:54.870 --> 00:09:58.470
So in summary, I told you a little bit about the infrastructure that you need to

165
00:09:58.610 --> 00:10:02.210
place, all of our capabilities, and last but not least,

166
00:10:02.450 --> 00:10:06.330
two-tiered governance system. And with that, I'll hand the podium to

167
00:10:06.350 --> 00:10:08.030
my friend and colleague, Dr. Topaloglu.

168
00:10:16.470 --> 00:10:18.990
Thank you, Shannon, and good afternoon, everyone.

169
00:10:19.040 --> 00:10:22.750
Thanks for coming to our panel. So I'll be talking a little bit about more

170
00:10:22.770 --> 00:10:26.650
technical details about our implementation and shifting from why

171
00:10:26.710 --> 00:10:29.770
and how we built to some of the clinical applications.

172
00:10:31.330 --> 00:10:34.630
So the core tension here is most in the room may

173
00:10:34.730 --> 00:10:38.410
agree that we know that getting patients into the right

174
00:10:38.450 --> 00:10:40.230
clinical trial changes outcomes.

175
00:10:40.830 --> 00:10:41.670
But the systems

176
00:10:42.690 --> 00:10:46.310
make it incredibly hard to identify who is eligible

177
00:10:46.750 --> 00:10:47.390
at the right

178
00:10:48.470 --> 00:10:51.570
point of care of the patients.

179
00:10:52.350 --> 00:10:55.990
And there are really four compounding problems that we see.

180
00:10:56.190 --> 00:11:00.050
First, trials are chronically under-enrolled,

181
00:11:00.490 --> 00:11:04.450
not because eligible patients don't exist, but because we can't

182
00:11:04.510 --> 00:11:08.250
find them efficiently. Second, the data we need to make

183
00:11:09.130 --> 00:11:12.930
that match is buried in unstructured texts

184
00:11:13.110 --> 00:11:17.030
like pathology reports, radiology, progress notes, and so on.

185
00:11:18.670 --> 00:11:22.550
Therefore, no structured fields tells cleanly some crucial

186
00:11:22.590 --> 00:11:24.870
information needed for matching.

187
00:11:25.430 --> 00:11:28.910
The third eligibility criteria are increasing the multi-model.

188
00:11:29.690 --> 00:11:33.530
You may have seen increasing imaging findings and molecular

189
00:11:33.590 --> 00:11:37.570
markers, and prior treatment history needed for

190
00:11:37.650 --> 00:11:41.590
the matching. And we talk a little bit about some of the work

191
00:11:41.630 --> 00:11:44.970
that we are doing at NCI about structuring eligibility criteria

192
00:11:45.010 --> 00:11:48.890
yesterday's panel, and happy to talk afterwards if needed.

193
00:11:48.950 --> 00:11:52.470
And the fourth is the obvious solution is training a powerful

194
00:11:52.590 --> 00:11:56.270
LLM on that data that runs

195
00:11:56.290 --> 00:11:58.810
directly into the privacy barrier.

196
00:11:59.130 --> 00:12:02.870
We cannot just aggregate PHI across institution to

197
00:12:02.940 --> 00:12:04.590
train a shared model easily.

198
00:12:05.590 --> 00:12:09.470
Therefore, further learning is with the foundation model fine-tuning

199
00:12:09.530 --> 00:12:12.530
is our way to get through that

200
00:12:12.570 --> 00:12:16.346
barrier.So what you are seeing here is full

201
00:12:16.386 --> 00:12:20.146
architecture end to end. On the left, each of our four participating

202
00:12:20.266 --> 00:12:23.626
sites, as Julie listed those, has

203
00:12:24.106 --> 00:12:27.726
its own local data, clinical text from EHR, radiology,

